Theodore Kaczynski, the Unabomber suspect, faces trial in Sacramento for bombings that killed two and injured others.
Arrested in Montana, he pleads not guilty to all charges.
Attorney General Janet Reno authorizes seeking the death penalty.
Jurors' identities are kept secret, with nearly 600 prospects interviewed.
Legal experts suggest Kaczynski may avoid the death penalty due to mental health issues.
The trial is expected to last up to six months.
Kaczynski's defense seeks a fair jury selection process.
The case has garnered significant media attention, with extensive coverage of the 17-year reign of terror.
